If I saying what I eat to maintain my body and it's 3,000 calories and then all the comp. As someone that eats over 30 100 calories a day, I wanna tap in here. No hate, no shade to this creator. She has a lot of great points. Like not comparing yourself to people on the internet, especially when they are years ahead of you and their fitness journey. But I wanna talk about how you get to eating that much food and maintaining it. And it's not the way you think. These people you see on the internet that are eating crazy amounts of foods, like 3,000 calories a day, have been doing this for years. And I don't mean like one to two, I mean like five to 10 years. The longer you lift and feel yourself properly, the more muscle mass your body gets. The more muscle mass your body has, the higher your basal metabolic rate is, which is the rate at which you burn calories at rest. So that means you need more fuel. So yes, after years and years and years of consistent weight training and fueling your body properly, you can imagine that it is possible for a woman to need that much fuel to maintain her body. Not to mention these people are eating Whole Foods. They are eating crap. They're fueling their bodies with nutrient dense foods. I have a lot of female clients that are currently eating around 24 25 calories A day and they're lifting four to five times a week. They're not doing any cardio or any extra condition. With all this being said, that is why weight training is one of the best options for losing fat and keeping it off in a sustainable way. Not to mention all of the other health benefits that come from weight training. You also can't compare walking to weight training and expect the same results.

video_description: #stitch with @Sarah Lauren Not trying to be rude in any way towards this young lady, I just think we need to be realistic and stop calling sweat suits “weight loss secrets”.  Sweat is the body’s natural A/C. It helps dilate blood vessels for easier transfer of blood cells throughout the body and also regulates the body’s temperature. While sweating is also wonderful for reducing water weight, thats ALL THAT IS BEING REDUCED…WATER. This young lady does state that water weight is lost. But we can’t call this a “weight loss” secret when there is no true weight being lost. You MAY see a difference of about 5lbs, but unless your body fat percentage is low enough, you won’t see a life changing difference. And unless you’re a few days out from a body building show, or trying to reduce your water retention for a particular event such as a photoshoot or a ufc fight, this isn’t going to be as effective as you would think. You can achieve this same technique by wearing something as simple as a few more layers. Maybe even a SWEAT shirt and a pair of SWEAT pants. You could even go as far as a simple trash bag underneath a hoodie if you want to reduce your water weight/water retention at a fraction of the cost. This is not a weight loss secret. voice_to_text: if you've ever been made fun of for your weight you can definitely relate to that for anybody new here I used to be 308 pounds morbidly obese and then I lost 140 so uh I think I know what I'm talking about when it comes to this I'm gonna tell you a few stories because most of the time when someone's making fun of you for your weight I can pretty much guarantee you that it's because they're incredibly insecure about their own going through school being 308 pounds myself put a big target on my back it was very easy to make fun of me so I got a lot of ridicule from other kids and nine times out of 10 it was often the guys who were very very good at football very kind of athletic but very skinny now fast forward a few years post weight loss I've actually had a few conversations with people who used to bully me in school and one of them I'll give him a lot of credit for this really matured and owned up and said to me hey Phil listen I'm really sorry for treating you the way that I did back in school I fucking hated my own appearance the guy hated his own body he felt really really insecure about how skinny he was how he thought he was small how he thought he'd never get a girlfriend because he was just that tiny and so he saw someone massive like me and decided yeah do you know what I'm gonna take out my insecurity on him to make myself feel better now and you know what I really respect the guy for that he'd obviously done a lot of introspection and maturing over the years and he apologized for it and we actually kind of talk on the regular now which is fun every now and then he even asks me about how he can build a little bit more muscle cause he's bulking you know because I'm also a personal trainer hit the follow button by the way of course there's a few other people from school who felt the same way he did but didn't mature as much as he did there was one guy who thought I was dating one of my friends and he cornered her in a bar one time because he was just basically like oh he used to be dead fat why you with him you could be with someone like me it sounds like cartoonishly stupid but it legitimately happened the dude was apparently borderline blackout drunk so it kind of shows how these feelings that he buried down deep will surface in moments like that in Uni I got given a lot of acting roles that were always designed to make fun of my weight I'd get cast in roles such as Big Billy or Stinky John and those were characters that I did not apply for which made it extra insulting and the guy responsible for giving me those castings actually contacted me around this time last year and we had a little conversation and in that he basically admitted that he had received castings that made fun of his weight in uni and he basically internalized that felt really insecure about his own body and then he took it out on me years later he didn't properly apologize and he said some other horrible things and tried to make himself out to be the victim but it doesn't justify you taking it out on other people does it probably the last example I'll use is a show that I did a little while ago a cast member had to leave and one of the cast members said to me oh yeah I'm glad we got rid of them they were too chubby to be in this play they were too chubby to play that role but the week before all this happened I was actually talking to that person and they were saying oh God I feel so fat I feel so horrible I've got to cut some weight before I do this show it's just oh I'm ugly I'm horrible I don't feel good about myself so I think it's pretty obvious to see why they went so hard in on that other person over their weight so I think moral of the story is if someone's making fun of you for your weight nine times out of 10 they are probably incredibly insecure about their own weight or their own appearance in some form and that will then often get vented and projected at you make of that what you will but me personally I guess I started to relate to them a little bit more and feel a bit more sympathy it's easy to think of yourself as the main character all the time so sometimes it benefits your own mental health to think about the fact that other people are probably just as complex as you I personally found a lot of peace in that because it allowed me to not take it too personally when people would then make fun of my weight and it's a big reason why I decided to become a personal trainer as well because I think pretty much all of us out there will struggle with our body image and confidence at some point instead of taking it out on others we might as well do something about it nothing worthwhile will ever be built if all you do is tear something else down you have to work on
